title: Do the top Quora writers get direct financial compensation? - Quora

response.answer_text: For reasons known only to Quora employees, I was nominated as a top writer in 2016 and 2017. By the time the 2017 nomination came I had answered just under 400 questions. For those two nominations, I had access to the following: One messenger bag (about $50-100)One Patagonia fleece (about $100 I think, maybe more)Invitation to two parties in the USA - I didn’t go since Quora didn’t include intercontinental airfares, but let’s guess that each one was worth about $50 in food and drinks.So my total “reward” has been around 75 cents per question. Which, now that I think about it, is not bad at all. But then I think about how much time I’ve spent using Quora, and the hourly rate is not so great. Still, it’s not bad for something I’d be doing for free anyway. The top writer thing is really a lottery - there are many people who write great stuff, and only a few who are lucky enough to be noticed through no fault of their own. In that sense, it’s a lot like literary prizes: extremely subjective, and impossible to please everyone.

The best example of a Quora writer effectively leveraging the platform is Jason Lemkin. Now before you go and try and carve out your niche and dominate a particular Quora topic and “Lemkins” it, let’s get a little background first. Jason was a “made” guy before he decided to contribute to Quora. He has successful exits in, surprise, surprise, SaaS startups. He was also a SaaS focused VC at well-known firm, Storm Ventures. So why am I mentioning Quora mattering for Jason Lemkins? It comes down to a recent TechCrunch article. Jason credits Quora for burnishing his reputation as one of the foremost experts in SaaS, and particularly SaaS investing. He has a new $70 million venture fund, SaaStr with a unique vetting process. Here’s the TC article. It is an interesting read. Jason Lemkin just raised a $70 million fund; here’s how he did it So now you are wondering how can I “Lemkins” a Quora category? Here’s his Quora resume: 23.9 million read answers,Top Writer 2013, 2014, 2015, 20161908 answersJason M. Lemkin

Before I discovered Quora I wrote in scraps of time between other things. These scattered fragments made me so very happy. Then, Quora came along. A whole site filled to the brim with the best ever writing prompts. I began to write more. It felt so good I determined to give more space to my writing, let it go from a crumbs to cake: a whole period of time dedicated just to that. Very quickly – within six months - I reorganized my entire life to properly accommodate my greatest source of joy. The most notable consequence of this is that now I see stories everywhere. I feel lit, and you can interpret that any way you want. Rather than wondering what to write about or when or feeling like I have this thing inside I’m going to get to some time in the indeterminate future, I instead ask myself what on Earth I did to score the greatest prize of all: the certainty that I will always be able to write something new. Of course Top Writers get paid. Just not in the way that you think.

Do the top Quora writers get paid? Short answer : YES. First of all I see a subtle nuance in the question, though I am not sure if it was intended or not. But in its present form it is asking about top Quora writers than about Quora Top Writers. Able to see the difference this makes? Having been a Quora Top Writer in 2015 and 2017 but remaining a top Quora writer all along, I can assure you I get paid - both handsomely and regularly - by way deserving compliments and educative insights. An up vote followed by an appreciative comment from a fellow writer whom you highly respect or a healthy debate involving some great insight with an experts whom you ardently admire are the greatest and the biggest payments for all the efforts you just put in while writing on Quora. This is just priceless and invaluable. Without these, what does a jacket could anyway mean to me in the sweltering climate of Chennai? It is the perennial compliments from people which matter more than the occasional complimentary from the company.

I am not a top writer but aspire to become one someday. I still remember last year when two of my answers went viral reaching close to 100k views each(they were later collapsed for image policy violation,but that is a separate topic of discussion). I could have never imagined to reach such a huge and diverse audience by any other medium. The joy that I was filled with couldn't be explained in words. It was such a raw emotion,I was overwhelmed.I felt so much gratitude towards people who took time out of their daily lives to go through my views.I also felt responsible to provide them with quality content. It provided me with great satisfaction,it provided me with an audience.Can that be weighed against a monetary balance,no way. I couldn't elucidate my feelings when a complete stranger shared it as a post in facebook. I was humbled when few people thanked me for my answers. That joyous feeling,my dear friend, outweighs and surpasses any monetary benefits.

They don’t get paid, but I hear the prizes are nifty. I have been on Quora for about 90 days or so and have 3,000 answers and 17 million answer views and nearly 30,000 followers and a top contributor to 109 categories, yet I am not a top writer? Based on that, I am not sure what criteria they use to make an award?

response.answer_text: No. Once a year Quora sends us a nice gift of some kind (for the past three years it has been a jacket or a bag) and twice a year Quora throws a party and invites us to attend at our own expense. We are not tangibly compensated in any other way.
We don’t get paid. We get rewarded. After writing over 3300 answers, in nearly 20 months, I am finally being rewarded with this jacket:  I am expecting to receive mine during the coming week. GV
Do the top Quora writers get direct financial compensation? No. We write because we want to share what we know.

The simple answer is No but you can get rewarded for your views by Getting recognised by the community.Getting more followers.Building a writing habit that help millions of people searching for ideas and knowledge over internet.http://Quora.com is not a race but a place where you share your thoughts,ideas and knowledge to the world for free.You can promote your products too which people may buy if it appeals to them. Concluding my answer money earning platforms are also available but Quora is to share your thoughts and ideas to rest of the world for free..Quora rewards best writers by providing them recognition which is great asset for anyone who has just started.

We are paid not by money but: Satisfaction of helping another personAppreciation from other QuoransHonors from getting a Top Writer icon on our profilePublication opportunities from other sites, notably Forbes or publicitySuper cool Patagonia jacket from QuoraMuch more effective than cash, if you ask me. However, Knowledge Prize answers chosen by the sponsor do get paid. If you’re only looking to make money, I suppose you could try inserting shameless plugs in your answers to redirect to ads or products on your blog.

Nope. Top Writers do not get payment from Quora. We do normally get some kind of gift. This year it was a jacket. Quora also has a meeting/party for Top Writers. But we have to get ourselves there, if we want to go.

No, they do not. If they did, then everyone would be writing answers just to get money, Quora would go bankrupt, there would be “whales” who spam to get views and in turn, money. Although they don’t get direct money, many of them open up YouTube channels so they get ad revenue from there. I’ve also heard that Top Writers get some goodies from Quora every now and then, but nothing that will put significant dent in Quora’s revenue. So no, they don’t get paid, and I think most Top Writers would agree when I say this: paying people for having a lot of views would discourage the love of writing and promote the love of money.

I do not know why you have asked me this question.However, I feel that top writers feel like writing on Quora, because it gives them an opportunity to share whatever they know with others. They may feel happy if someone benefits out of what they have written. Moreover, they may really like what they do.Some people may like to interact with others just for the sake of it. I have started to write on Quora only recently ; I do it because I like to participate in it and I want to keep myself intellectually stimulated.

Thanks for A2A, First of all I am not a top writer. Further for your direct financial compensation part, No Quora doesn't provide any financial compensation but it does provide non financial compensation in form of T shirts, jacket and such other stuff as confirmed by top writers. Further Quora also helps in learning many things and upgrading your knowledge which i think is best ever compensation one can provide. Sayonara with a thank you note for reading.

Pay the top writers directly? No. But Quora has some expenses related to Top Writers, including the yearly giveaways described here: What was contained in the Top Writers welcome package each year? and the incremental costs of adding the Top Writer functionality to the software product, like writing some code and designing the icons.

Quora is basically a knowledge sharing website where people share their knowledge. It doesn't pay anyone to write answers. Yes, You can consider it a platform for gaining knowledge and improving your writing skills. When it comes to making money online, You can use it as an Indirect tool.
